{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Class E sortases are membrane-bound cysteine transpeptidases distributed in Gram-positive bacteria (mainly present in Actinobacteria). Genes encoding class A and E sortases are never found in the same organism, and similar to class A sortases, the genes encoding class E sortases are not positioned adjacent to genes encoding potential protein substrates, suggesting a housekeeping sortase function of class E sortases in some high G + C Gram-positive bacteria [[cite:PUB00092196]]. Similar to class A sortase, class E sortases are capable of anchoring a large number of functionally distinct surface proteins containing a cell wall sorting signal to an amino group located on the bacterial cell wall. They recognize an LAXTG sorting signal, instead of the canonical LPXTG motif processed by class A sortases [[cite:PUB00081159]].</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The prototypical class E sortase from Corynebacterium diphtheria (named Cd-SrtF) is a non-polymerization sortase that is not required for pilus polymerization, and proceeds to complete the assembly process by anchoring the polymer to the cell wall peptidoglycan [[cite:PUB00081161]]. Moreover, in Streptomyces coelicolor, one or both of Staphylococcus aureus SrtA homologues may function as class E sortase responsible for the cell wall anchoring of the long chaplin proteins (ChpA-C) containing an LAXTG sorting signal, which presumably mediate aerial hyphae formation [[cite:PUB00092211], [cite:PUB00092212]]. The family also includes some class E sortase homologs from Gram-negative and Archaebacterial species, but the functions of these enzymes are unknown [[cite:PUB00013027]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "5utt", "name" "SrtA sortase from Actinomyces oris"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR023365", "name" "Sortase domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"cdd" {"cd05830" "Sortase do